requests.name: Create an action type
requests.description: Create a new action type.

requests.name: Read all action types
requests.description: Read all action types.  The action types are returned with the built-in types coming first, followed by the custom types sorted by descending creation date.

requests.name: Create an action
requests.description: Create a new action of the specified type. `all` can be specified as the `actionType`, in which case the specified action type must be supplied in the payload. If no location is specified, the Platform will automatically determine the location based on the IP address of the device who has issued it, along with a country code that is returned in the context object.

requests.name: Read all actions of a type
requests.description: Read all actions of the specified `actionType` visible to the authenticating API key. `all` can be used as the `actionType` to view actions of all types.

requests.name: Update an action type
requests.description: Update an action type with new metadata.

requests.name: Delete an action type
requests.description: Delete an action type.

requests.name: Read an action
requests.description: Read a single action by ID. You can use `all` as an `actionType` to read actions of unknown type.

requests.name: Delete an action
requests.description: Delete an action by ID.

requests.name: Read an action with context
requests.description: Read a single action by ID with context. The `?context=true` query parameter can be used to include the context field in the action read.

requests.name: Create an application
requests.description: Create an application within a project. The object returned contains the `appApiKey` parameter, which is an Application API key that must be used within an external application to issue calls to the API. However, because this API key can be hard coded within external applications (e.g. mobile/JS) and is visible to anyone, it can be used only for a very limited set of operations (create users, read a product, send actions etc.).

requests.name: Read all applications
requests.description: Read all applications inside the specified project.

requests.name: Read an application
requests.description: Read an application by `applicationId` in the project specified by `projectId`.

requests.name: Update an application
requests.description: Update an application by `applicationId`.

requests.name: Delete an application
requests.description: Delete an application by `applicationId`.

requests.name: Read self application
requests.description: Read the self application of the authenticating Trusted App API Key.

requests.name: Update self application
requests.description: Update the self application of the authenticating Trusted App API Key.

requests.name: Read Trusted App API Key
requests.description: Read the Trusted Application API key for the application with `applicationId`. This is a secret key that has access to more endpoints than the standard Application API key.

requests.name: Create an Application User
requests.description: Create a new unactivated Application User with a unique email address. The response contains an `activationCode` that must be returned to the API (See 'Activate an Application User') before it can access the API. This gives the client application an opportunity to ensure the email address has been validated.

requests.name: Activate an Application User
requests.description: Activate a new Application User using the `activationCode` provided in the 'Create an Application User' step.

requests.name: Create an anonymous user
requests.description: Create an anonymous Application User. These users are not associated with a real person, and are useful for tracking anonymous interactions.

requests.description: Read a single Application User but their `evrythngUser` ID.

requests.name: Update an Application User
requests.description: Update an existing Application User by their `evrythngUser` ID. Authorised Application Users can modify their own data (including the password) using their API key.

requests.name: Delete an Application User
requests.description: Delete an Application User by its `evrythngUser` ID.

requests.name: Log an Application User out
requests.description: Log an Application User out and invalidate their Application User API key.

requests.name: Log an Application User in
requests.description: Authenticate (log in) an existing user using their original `email` and `password` used at creation time.

requests.name: Log In with Access Info
requests.description: Log an Application User in and obtain access details.

requests.name: Create a connector
requests.description: To enable a third party integration for a specific application, `POST` a connector model describing the configuration of the connection with the third party cloud. Only the Operator can enable connectors in an application. For Nest connectors, the `auth` credentials can be found in the Nest Developers console.

requests.name: Update a connector
requests.description: Update a single connector by name. Not all the fields of a connector can be updated. If the authentication parameters changed, this is considered to be a new connector and it must to be created separately as a new resource.

requests.name: Delete a connector

requests.description: Remove a Thng from a collection. There is a limit of 500 Thngs removed per API call on collections. If your collection contains more than 500 elements you should consider an iterative solution.

A successful HTTP `POST` will create a `FileDocument` record with a unique ID and a transient `uploadUrl` field. This signed `uploadUrl` can then be used by a client with an HTTP `PUT` request to do the actual upload to remote storage. The `uploadUrl` will expire after 30 minutes. The input payload to this endpoint should also contain a setting for the `privateAccess` field to indicate whether the file should have

requests.name: Create/update product properties
requests.description: Create/update a product's properties. When a resource is created, you can specify an initial set of properties and their values. To update those properties or to add new ones, use a `PUT` request with an array of `PropertyDocument` JSON objects containing the changed fields. If the properties updated do not exist, they are created automatically by this request and no error/notification will be returned.

requests.name: Read product properties
requests.description: Read all properties on a product. The returned payload is the complete array of all the properties with the last value of each.

requests.name: Read a product property
requests.description: Read a single product property. By default, all the updates of this property are returned using pagination in a reverse history fashion (the first element of the returned array is the latest update). For accessing only a subset of all the updates to a single property, you can specify a time range using `?from=Timestamp` and `?to=Timestamp` to specify respectively the beginning and end of the time window. You will receive an array of all the property updates during this time.

requests.name: Update a product property
requests.description: Update a single property by `key`.

requests.name: Delete a product property
requests.description: Delete a product property. Property updates are not uniquely identified (do not have their own URL). Therefore, the only way to delete data points is to append the `?to=Timestamp` URL query parameter to specify a point in time before which all the data points will be removed. If the `?to=` parameter is not specified, ALL updates of this property will be deleted!

requests.name: Create/update Thng properties
requests.description: Create/update Thng properties. When a resource is created, you can specify an initial set of properties and their values. To update those properties or to add new ones, use a `PUT` request with an array of `PropertyDocument` JSON objects containing the changed fields. If the properties updated do not exist, they are created automatically by this request and no error/notification will be returned.

requests.name: Update a Thng property
requests.description: Update a single Thng property by `key`.

requests.name: Read a Thng property

By default, all the updates of this property are returned using pagination in a reverse history fashion (the first element of the returned array is the latest update). For accessing only a subset of all the updates to a single property, you can specify a time range using `?from=Timestamp` and `?to=Timestamp` to specify respectively the beginning and end of the time window. You will receive an array of all the property updates during this time.

requests.name: Delete a Thng property
requests.description: Delete a Thng property. Property updates are not uniquely identified (do not have their own URL). Therefore, the only way to delete data points is to append the `?to=Timestamp` URL query parameter to specify a point in time before which all the data points will be removed. If the `?to=` parameter is not specified, ALL updates of this property will be deleted!

requests.name: Create an Application User role
requests.description: Create a new Application User role. Only the account owner can create new roles. You cannot create roles with the same `name` as the predefined `admin` and `none` roles. Roles `name`s are considered unique. This means two roles with different `id`s cannot share the same `name`.

requests.description: Delete a role by ID. The predefined `none` role will be assigned to all the users currently having the role about to be removed. A `userInApp` role cannot be deleted until all users with that role have been assigned a different role.

requests.name: Update role permissions
requests.description: Update the set of permissions for a role with a new set. The payload replaces the old set of permissions for this role. This must include any existing permissions, otherwise they will be deleted if not present in the new payload. To remove a permission, simply omit it in the payload after reading from the role initially.

requests.name: Update a Thng's location
requests.description: Update a Thng's location. The payload must always be an array of `LocationDocument` objects, which allows you to send several locations (with different timestamps each) in a single request. This is useful when a device wants to update a path cached over a certain period of time at once. An example would be a taxi that updates the whole set of locations it has been through once per hour instead of sending each GPS sensor reading individually.

requests.name: Delete a Thng location history
requests.description: Delete a Thng's location history. If the `?to=Timestamp` query parameter with timestamp is not specified, all history for this property will be deleted.

If called multiple times for the same Thng, the existing API key will be returned (a new one will not be generated). If you want to create a new API key for a Thng, you must delete the existing one first.
